{"news_desk": "National", "print_page": "1", "section_name": "The Upshot", "subsection_name": null, "byline": {"contributor": "David Leonhardt reported from Washington, Amanda Cox from New York, and Claire Cain Miller from San Francisco. Dave McKinney contributed reporting from Wood Dale, Ill.", "original": "By DAVID LEONHARDT, AMANDA COX and CLAIRE CAIN MILLER", "person": [{"rank": 1, "role": "reported", "firstname": "David", "organization": "", "lastname": "LEONHARDT"}, {"rank": 2, "role": "reported", "firstname": "Amanda", "organization": "", "lastname": "COX"}, {"middlename": "Cain", "firstname": "Claire", "lastname": "MILLER", "rank": 3, "role": "reported", "organization": ""}]}, "abstract": "The Upshot; new study set for publication by Equality of Opportunity Project suggests that geographic location has enormous impact on upward mobility for poor people; data upends grim findings of Moving to Opportunity anti-poverty study 20 years earlier, which seemed to show that poor families did not benefit after being moved to better neighborhoods; report comes amid climate of deep unrest concerning inequality.", "type_of_material": "News", "word_count": "1813", "lead_paragraph": "A decades-old effort found that moving poor families to better neighborhoods did little to help them. A new look at the data suggests the opposite.", "pub_date": "2015-05-04T00:00:00Z", "document_type": "article", "slideshow_credits": null, "headline": {"main": "An Atlas of Upward Mobility Shows Paths Out of Poverty", "content_kicker": "Importance of Place", "print_headline": "Change of Address Offers a Pathway Out of Poverty", "kicker": "The Upshot"}, "snippet": "A decades-old effort found that moving poor families to better neighborhoods did little to help them. A new look at the data suggests the opposite.", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/05/03/us/04UP-Poverty1/04UP-Poverty1-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"widewidth": "190", "wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/05/03/us